{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 15:23:27.699704", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\n\nSummary\n- Overall control-plane (OSPF) and server-side connectivity appear mostly healthy: core routers have OSPF-learned routes for the tenant subnets and the server-access router advertises/has the 10.200.0.0/24 network locally.\n- There are clear data-plane anomalies: packet loss and reachability inconsistencies affecting a subset of hosts toward the server farm (load_balancer and web servers) and some host-to-host flows.\n- The problem appears localized to a small set of access/edge hosts (and their immediate access-switch paths) rather than the server farm or core routers. There is one additional suspicious control-plane detail on the server_access_router (no fully adjacent OSPF neighbors listed) worth further investigation.\n\nEvidence and key observations (from collected tool outputs)\n1) Host-to-server packet loss (strong signal)\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): 4 tx, 1 rx, 75% loss (rtt_avg 2.057 ms)\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 4 tx, 2 rx, 50% loss\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> web_server_1 (10.200.0.4): 4 tx, 2 rx, 50% loss\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> web_server_2 (10.200.0.5): 4 tx, 2 rx, 50% loss\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> web_server_3 (10.200.0.6): 4 tx, 3 rx, 25% loss\n\nThese losses are significant and repeat across the set of web endpoints; they indicate packet-loss on the path from that source toward the server farm (not just one destination).\n\n2) Other inter-host losses (localized)\n- host_1_2_1_1 -> host_1_1_1_2 (10.1.1.13): 4 tx, 2 rx, 50% loss\n- host_1_2_1_1 -> host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.11): 4 tx, 2 rx, 50% loss\n- host_2_2_1_2 -> some other internal hosts report 0% loss, so problem is not universal for that host\n\n3) Server-side and backend behavior (healthy)\n- dhcp_server -> load_balancer, web_server_0..3 and dns_server: 0% loss and low latency\n- backend_web_* -> load_balancer: 0% loss\n- load_balancer -> dns_server: 0% loss\n\nThis indicates the server-side path (server_access_router, server farm switches, load balancer, web servers) is responsive and not broadly dropping traffic. The losses are therefore asymmetric: some hosts see drops toward the servers, while servers and other sources do not show drops to clients.\n\n4) OSPF / routing snapshot\n- router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3 — OSPF routes to 10.1.x and 10.2.x are present (routes look healthy).\n- server_access_router routes: 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected and present in routing table (br0). OSPF diagnosis shows:\n  - \"Number of fully adjacent neighbors in this area: 0\" on server_access_router (Area 0). The router nevertheless shows LSAs and routes. This is unusual and should be noted (it may be a consequence of point-to-point links or passive interfaces, or adjacency issues), but routing appears to be functioning for advertised networks.\n\n5) Host local interface configs (odd findings)\n- get_host_net_config run on host_2_2_1_2 and host_1_2_1_1 returned ifconfig/ip_addr outputs that show the interfaces are up but do not show an IPv4 address in the ip addr output (no inet 10.x/24 present). This conflicts with mapping in the reachability dataset (those hosts appear to have 10.x addresses in the reachability mapping), but the absence of an explicit IPv4 address in the net-config output is abnormal and should be validated. (Possible cause: the net-config snapshot was taken in a different context, or the host has a transient DHCP/stack issue.)\n\nDevices and links localized as likely affected\n- host_2_2_1_2 — consistently shows elevated packet loss toward the server farm. Immediate suspects:\n  - host NIC / OS networking stack on host_2_2_1_2\n  - the access switch port for host_2_2_1_2 (topology suggests switch_access_2_1_1)\n  - the uplink from that access switch to its distribution router (router_dist_2_1) or the distribution router port itself\n- host_1_2_1_1 — shows 50% loss to some hosts. Immediate suspects:\n  - host NIC / OS networking on host_1_2_1_1\n  - its access switch port (likely switch_access_1_1_1)\n  - link between that access switch and distribution router\n- Core and server-side devices (router_core_1/2/3, server_access_router, load_balancer, web servers) — evidence indicates these are broadly functioning: servers can ping one another and the load balancer and DHCP server can reach web servers with 0% loss.\n\nRoot-cause hypotheses (ranked)\n1) Access-layer/local host problem (highest likelihood)\n- Rationale: Packet loss is concentrated to specific hosts (host_2_2_1_2, host_1_2_1_1) and their immediate flows. Server-side tests from DHCP/backend hosts show no loss. This pattern is typical of NIC issues (driver/duplex errors), faulty switch port, flapping link, or local congestion/queuing/dropping at the access switch port for the affected hosts.\n- Supporting evidence: High loss percentages (50–75%) from a single host to multiple servers, while other sources have 0% loss. The local ifconfig for host_2_2_1_2 shows TX/RX counters with no interface errors recorded in that snapshot, but the absence of a visible IPv4 address in the ip addr output is suspicious.\n\n2) Intermittent port/switch error or configuration (moderate likelihood)\n- Rationale: If the access-switch uplink or distribution switch has intermittent errors or misconfiguration (eg. rate-limiting, ACLs, or mis-set spanning-tree causing transient drops), that could drop traffic from those subnets toward the server farm while other subnets are unaffected.\n- Supporting evidence: Multiple hosts on separate access switches show packet loss to other hosts; this could indicate per-access-switch problems.\n\n3) Asymmetric routing or filtering on server_access_router or load_balancer (lower likelihood)\n- Rationale: If return traffic is being allowed but forward traffic from some subnets dropped by an ACL or by a firewall/anti-spoofing rule, you'd also see loss only in certain directions or from certain source subnets.\n- Counter-evidence: Server-access router shows the server network connected and other clients reach servers without loss; servers themselves can reach clients. Also the loss is observed to multiple server endpoints — less consistent with per-subnet ACL filtering unless specifically targeted.\n\n4) OSPF/control-plane oddity on server_access_router (investigate)\n- Rationale: server_access_router's OSPF status indicates \"Number of fully adjacent neighbors in this area: 0\" which is unusual. If adjacencies are not formed as expected, route propagation or transient route flaps could cause packet drops for some traffic flows.\n- Counter-evidence: server_access_router has the 10.200.0.0/24 connected and other devices have routes to it; core routers show expected OSPF routes. So although the OSPF adjacency count looks odd, it does not presently explain the specific host-limited packet loss.\n\nAdditional observations / inconsistencies\n- Several ping results in the collected matrix are marked \"unknown\" (no test result). This appears to be due to limited source coverage of the tests rather than absolute loss; it complicates comprehensive inference across all hosts.\n- The get_host_net_config outputs for two checked hosts show no IPv4 inet line, which is inconsistent with the mapping used by the reachability matrix. That needs verification — if hosts intermittently lose their IPv4 address (DHCP issues), that would also cause reachability problems.\n\nRecommended next diagnostic checks (for the team, not remediation)\n- On affected hosts (host_2_2_1_2 and host_1_2_1_1):\n  - Re-check local ip address (ip addr), interface statistics (ethtool -S / ethtool eth0), and kernel NIC error counters to confirm/deny hardware or duplex errors.\n  - Check ARP table and default route presence.\n- On their access switches (switch_access_2_1_1 and switch_access_1_1_1):\n  - Inspect interface counters for the host-facing ports and uplinks (CRC/frame errors, drops, link flaps).\n  - Check port configuration (speed/duplex) and whether any rate-limits or ACLs are applied to the ports/subnet.\n- On distribution routers uplink to core for the affected subnets:\n  - Review interface counters and OSPF neighbor states.\n- Re-run targeted pings/traceroutes from the affected hosts toward the load_balancer/web_server addresses and capture where packet loss first appears (collect per-hop loss).\n- Verify server_access_router OSPF neighbor states in vtysh and confirm intended adjacency configuration (passive interfaces, point-to-point links, etc.) to explain the \"0 fully adjacent neighbors\" metric.\n\nConclusions\n- There is a clear, localized data-plane anomaly: significant packet loss from at least one access host (host_2_2_1_2) toward the server farm and additional host-to-host losses involving host_1_2_1_1.\n- The server farm and core routers appear healthy and reachable from many other sources — the fault is most likely at the access-layer (host NIC or access switch port/uplink) for the affected hosts.\n- There is an OSPF adjacency oddity on server_access_router to examine, though routing seems to be functioning for advertised networks; this is a secondary concern to validate.\n\nIf you want, I can perform targeted follow-up checks now (examples):\n- run ethtool and interface counters on the affected hosts and their distribution/access routers,\n- run traceroute (with multiple packets) from an affected host toward the load_balancer to localize the hop where loss occurs,\n- show OSPF neighbor/state on server_access_router and on the adjacent core/distribution routers.\n\n(Per your request I did not include mitigation steps — only detection, localization, evidence and root-cause hypotheses.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 36169, "output_tokens": 4825, "total_tokens": 40994, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 35456}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2496}}}
